Framework Fortresses: How Infrastructure Secures Its Place in the AI Agent Stack

Andrew Dyer

Dec 12, 2024 ⋅  12 min read

Key Insights

  • Autonomous AI agents, now capable of iterative reasoning, tool usage, and sophisticated decision-making, are emerging as practical, data-driven problem-solvers across different verticals.
  • While individual agent tokens may capture fleeting attention, their long-term value is more uncertain; the foundational infrastructure that supports many agents simultaneously will likely maintain more durable growth.
  • ai16z and Virtuals demonstrate how the infrastructure layer can build lasting competitive advantages through network effects, developer engagement, and value accrual—ultimately creating moats that standalone agents struggle to match.
  • As the space quickly evolves, individual agents may morph into frameworks with take rates themselves.

The size of the SaaS market is estimated to be around $330 billion and expected to grow to $1 trillion by 2032. Y Combinator says that the vertical AI agent market could be ten times bigger. The rise of autonomous AI agents represents one of the most significant shifts in the digital economy. These agents—capable of executing complex tasks, reasoning iteratively, and leveraging APIs—are quickly becoming important players in areas ranging from creative industries to consumer-facing applications. Enabled by improving foundational models and agentic workflows, agents are no longer just simple chatbots. They can now plan, improve upon their own outputs, and interact with ecosystems of other agents, protocols, and data sources. As a result, they are quickly moving from amusements into powerful, specialized problem-solvers. Agents will conduct onchain transactions for us through natural language prompts (like Griffain), act as a seamless interface between us and varying applications (like Orbit), and become tireless research assistants who can sift through and distill incoming information (like aixbt).

However, as crypto investors consider where best to place their capital in this shifting landscape, it is essential to distinguish between excitement surrounding individual “agent tokens” and the more foundational layers of the agent stack. While singular agents may achieve brief cultural relevance, their long-term value is less certain. In contrast, the underlying infrastructure—encompassing open-source frameworks, platform protocols, and the orchestration layers that enable agent interaction and scalability—holds more durable growth potential.

This research piece will explore why infrastructure-level projects may have more of a sustainable moat versus individual agents.

The L1-App: Framework-Agent Parallel

Individual AI agents may struggle to stay relevant over the long run for several reasons. They are emerging when this technological primitive is still in its formative stage, lacking established standards, interoperability protocols, and clear user expectations. Similar to early apps on new blockchains—where scalability, security, and usability were uncertain—these initial agents face evolving best practices, unpredictable demand, and infrastructure improvements that can quickly outpace their original designs. In contrast, platforms and launchpads that provide foundational tools and frameworks derive value from every new agent built on top of them, regardless of whether those agents thrive. This mirrors the dynamic seen with Layer 1 blockchains, which have consistently outlasted many of the first apps developed on their networks.

This pattern isn’t unique to blockchains or AI agents. In the early PC era, operating systems and chipmakers shaped the industry for decades, while initial software offerings often faded as technology advanced. The same happened in the smartphone era, with Apple and Google establishing enduring ecosystems as many early apps quickly lost relevance. We’re likely to see a similar trend in the AI agent space, where foundational infrastructure outlasts the first wave of agents.

Over time, some standout agent “apps” may solidify their presence, but early in the cycle, the safer thesis lies in the infrastructure layer that catalyzes and underpins them all. Obviously, there is going to be major competition at the infrastructure level as well, and we will detail some differences among emerging players in the space.

The Rise and Fall of Individual Agents

Since Goatseus kickstarted the agent meta, the landscape and performance of individual agents has shifted drastically. GOAT’s parabolic rise ended in mid-November with a crescendo of media attention, exchange listings, and dominant mindshare. The token topped around $1.2 billion in market cap. Simultaneously, we saw the rise of Luna (on the Virtuals platform), whose anime aesthetic, 24/7 live-streaming, and peek into her planning and execution process attracted a ton of attention. LUNA briefly spiked to around $230 million market cap at the end of October.

But the novelty of a fine-tuned LLM posting edgy tweets - or trying to create an army of “kittens,” in Luna’s case - seemed to have worn off quickly. Mindshare and engagement shifted to “reply guy” agents like Dolos and more creative agents like Zerebro, which create short-form videos and even music on Spotify. Competing for attention has been an uphill battle for individual agents, and will continue to be as launching a unique agent becomes easier and easier with launchpad platforms. While the earliest agents like GOAT and LUNA may make a comeback at some point, thus far mere provenance is not being heavily rewarded by the market.

Agents that focus solely on social engagement will likely face heavy competition and dilution pressures. On the other hand, there is still room for specialized agents to provide unique value to users to differentiate themselves. AIXBT, a research analyst agent launched by 0xrbt, recently topped the mindshare charts as it continues to push out high-value tweets related to onchain data and emerging narratives within crypto. While not flawless, AIXBT’s ability to scrape a massive amount of data from Twitter and other onchain data sources, summarize information into concise pitches, and quickly respond to user questions has made it immensely popular over the past month. Access to the AIXBT terminal - where you can directly prompt it and access data - currently costs 600,000 tokens (around $100,000 at today’s prices). While this pricing model may change, it is more closely approaching an actual service business in the real world: provide useful service, accrue actual value.

However, even agents with real utility and incentive for holding the underlying token are prone to capital rotations and eventually competition on the actual service provided. The space is moving so quickly that tokens that were considered beta to other tokens (like FARTCOIN to GOAT) may be decoupling. Well-established AI teams like Nous are even launching their own Twitter agents with large followings. Individual agents that do not compete on mere social metrics will ultimately have to provide some sort of useful service that is difficult to replicate because it is built and fine-tuned by teams with real domain expertise.

Framework Moats and Value Accrual

While a few individual agents captured initial mindshare and went through fairly fast hype cycles, the market seems to be positioning behind the infrastructure layer now. AI16Z recently flipped GOAT in market capitalization, and VIRTUAL moved past the $1 billion mark in late November. Let’s explore this widening gap in valuations.

Developer Activity and Network Effects

Eliza is an open-source, multi-agent framework designed to deploy and manage diverse autonomous agents. It is currently the number one trending repository on Github, has been forked over 1000 times, and has seen tremendous activity among more than 130 contributors. Eliza-based agents have numerous features including:

  • Long-term memory management and context awareness
  • Media processing (links, audio, video)
  • Multi-platform engagement (Discord, Telegram, Twitter) and multi-chain compatibility (expanding to more chains like Avalanche, Near, Aptos, and others)
  • Local inference with open-source models
  • Multiple agent use cases including assistants, influencer personas, and interactive characters

In this context, why is developer activity so important? For one, a large and active community of developers can rapidly iterate, introduce new features, fix bugs, and optimize performance at a much faster pace than a small, centralized team. More eyes on the codebase means more rigorous testing and quality control; plus, the framework will benefit from more contributors with diverse backgrounds and different domains of expertise. Additionally, strong engagement leads to the creation of complementary plugins and integrations. Story Protocol is already planning on bringing “programmable IP” to the Eliza framework - this integration would theoretically allow agents to make use of licensed IP through smart contracts across a swath of applications and platforms.

Entire ecosystems and new capabilities are being built on top of the open-source Eliza library, including:

  • Reality Spiral, which expanded Eliza agents’ ability to read, create, and invoke smart contracts
  • Abyss World, an RPG game with Eliza agents for NPCs
  • Echo Chambers, a chat platform API for agents which allows for safe testing and fine-tuning
  • The Great Onchain Agent Toolkit, which allows agents to more seamlessly connect to onchain apps with an SDK sponsored by Crossmint

Continued plugins, integrations, and enhancements will all likely cement Eliza as one of the major standards for building new AI agents. This positive flywheel of more features and growing ecosystems will create a stronger network effect relative to competitors.

While Virtuals does not have the same rapid, open-source developer activity, their agents can be ported to different platforms like Roblox (ex: for NPC agents within games) and can be customized for unique services like white-hat bounty hunting. More than 10,000 agents have been launched thus far, and integrations with other AI and gaming teams (Seraph, Pond Hub, and GAM3S.GG, to name a few) are ongoing. As they develop new tools and features for agent deployers, they should attract similar complementary ecosystems and integrations that drive flows back to the platform. These characteristics ultimately comprise moats that individual agents may struggle to attain.

Value Accrual

Value accrual for the VIRTUAL token is perhaps more straightforward than for AI16Z. The creator of the agent locks a specified amount of VIRTUAL tokens to create a bonding curve for the agent’s token, paired with VIRTUAL. Once the bonding curve hits $420,000, a liquidity pool (LP) of the agent token and VIRTUAL is created. The deployer becomes the owner of the locked LP for ten years to ensure stability. A 1% tax is incurred on all agent token trades as a means of bootstrapping some resources for inference and compute for individual agents.

Post-launch, real-world users may pay for services from the agent, a portion of which goes to the agent's onchain treasury (for future growth and operational costs). Inference costs are also paid in pre-loaded VIRTUAL tokens from the agent’s wallet. Periodic buyback and burns of the agent token occur after enough revenue accumulates in the treasury, reducing the supply. All trades for agent tokens must be made against VIRTUAL, so the increased success and revenue generation of underlying agent tokens leads directly to demand for the VIRTUAL token. Users, creators, and app developers thus all stand to benefit from an individual agent’s success. VIRTUAL essentially places itself as the gas token for a growing L1 ecosystem.

AI16Z (the token) value accrual is a bit more ambiguous. Ai16z itself operates as a decentralized autonomous organization (DAO) that leverages an autonomous AI agent to manage a pooled treasury—effectively acting as a venture capital fund, but without traditional human decision-makers. The decisions are left to an Eliza agent named “Marc AIndreessen,” who assigns trust scores to investors and contributors from the DAO that he interacts with. DAO members are also maintainers and creators of the Eliza repo and seek to advance agentic capabilities more widely. As such, the DAO has a type of gentlemen’s agreement with new teams in the agent space: if you launch using the Eliza framework, you donate 10% of the token supply to the DAO, and the DAO will give you contributor roles on the Eliza repo (and perhaps highlight wins by your team along the way).

Thus far, the DAO has accumulated around $12 million in agent tokens from various teams, including tokens launched by the DAO itself, like ELIZA. Obviously, with AI16Z (the token) valued at around $600 million, the market is not valuing the project according to its assets under management. The market is either using AI16Z as the best trade expression of bullishness around the Eliza framework itself, or it may be expecting a rapid proliferation of agents that would send 10% of their supply to the DAO. Agent launchpad vvvaifu.fun also integrated Eliza agents. The platform automatically sends 5% of a launched token’s supply to the DAO. It is possible that more third-party platforms implement this type of model in order to get support and partnerships with the core team.

Looking Ahead

The crypto agent space is in its infancy, and winners have yet to be chosen. Value accrual models - like token donations or supply burns - are still being designed and experimented with. However, fine-tuned or free-based LLMs with tokens attached are likely not where most of the value will accrue. From this brief period, we have already seen how individual agents may become commoditized or at least struggle to maintain mindshare for an extended period. For now, the infrastructure layer likely holds more promise with its frameworks being much more difficult to replicate and maintain at a rapid pace of change. We should, however, be paying attention to agents that aim to evolve into more than just social media personas, namely:

  • Zerebro, whose main developer is aiming to ship his own agent framework called Zerepy, that others can use to launch agents with similar social media functionality.
  • Dolos, whose main developer is building Dolion, a one-click deploy agent framework. This specific framework requires burning BULLY, similar to Virtuals’ design.

It’s unclear whether small, individual teams behind a singular agent will be able to compete with open-source frameworks or established teams that have been working for multiple years. But protocols focused on creating moats at the infrastructure level will likely be much more durable than standalone agents that only attain mindshare for a short period of time. The protocols that establish the largest network effects in the coming months will likely take the lion’s share of dollar value growth of the entire agent space, just as most of the value accrued to the top L1s.
